MICROBES FROM MARS: PRECAUTIONS (02)
************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Microbes from Mars: precautions 980218225243
Date: Fri, 20 Feb 1998 10:37:27 +0100
From: Fernando Dias de Avila Pires e Adriana Mohr <piresmohr@hol.fr>

In relation to the postings on microbes on Mars, I suggest reading three
chapters of George G. Simpson's book, "This view of life", Harcourt, Brace,
New York, 1964 (still very up to date) They reprint a critique of such
NASA projects, published by Simpson.
George Simpson approaches the subject from an evolutionary point of view,
showing the improbability, if not sheer impossibility that such complex
organisms as viruses and bacteria could have developed twice: on the Earth
and on Mars (or wherever else). Life evolved from the interaction of long
carbon chains or polymers with a certain type of (changing) environment,
and evolution is a process where chance plays a major role: chance
mutation, chance selection, chance survival. I would be better off playing
roulette at Monte Carlo with my eyes closed, on a [crooked wheel!
Viruses are adapted to live and reproduce in animal or plant cells.
Discounting Saint George's horse and the saint himself, where else [could
a virus live?
Furthermore', Simpson remarks that "Another curious fact is that a large
proportion of those now discussing this biological subject [NASA's space
bioscience, exobiology are not biologists. ... It would seem obvious that
organic evolution has a crucial bearing on the subject, which is
essentially a problem in evolutionary systematics."
Add to all that Francois Jacob's words:. "Ce qui caracterise le monde
vivant, ce sont a la fois sa diversite apparente et son unite sous-jacente.
.... Assurement, la vie ne pouvait se constituer qu'apres l'apparition de
nombreaux types moleculaires. Tous les composes qui caracterisent le monde
vivant ont necessairement du se former au cours de l'evolution chimique qui
a precede l'evolution biologique. Mais une fois la vie commencee sous forme
de quelque organisme primitif capable de se reproduire, c'est sourtout par
le remaniement des composes existants que devait se poursuivre l'evolution.
Avec l'apparition de proteines nouvelles ont pu se developer des fonctions
nouvelles. Mais ces proteines ne pouvaient etre que des variations sur des
themes connus. Une sequence de mille nucleotides determine la structure
d'une proteine de taille moyenne. La probabilite de voir une proteine
fonctionelle de se former de novo, par association au hasard d'acides
amines, est pratiquement zero.... Durant la majeure partie de l'evolution
biologique, la creation de structures moleculaires ne pouvait se fonder que
sur un remaniement de structures preexistantes. ... L'evolution biologique
est ainsi fondee sur une sorte de bricolage moleculaire, sur la
reutilization constante du vieux pour faire du neuf." (Jacob, Francois,
1981. Le jeu des possibles. Fayards, Paris.)
And so [with our dreams and imagination. The fantastic imaginary
creatures of medieval and Rennaissance times have been transmuted into
Martians and such. And we would be back discussing the question of
biogenesis versus abiogenesis - we'd better bring Pasteur and Tyndall back
to life. Or Creationism.
--
