[Creationism is still alive and kicking in the USA! For those who do not
read French, the gist of Jacob's text is that evolution builds on
pre-existing structures, first chemical and then organic, and the
probability of such a sequence resulting in life twice over is
infinitesimal.
However, I have always understood that there has been enough time in the
Universe for random permutations of chemicals to have resulted in life on
more than one occasion. As an avid science fiction fan, I was struck by
the suggestion in one story -- possibly by Asimov -- that life forms could
exist on hot planets based on silicon instead of carbon and on sulphur
bonds (the temperature being above the melting point of sulphur) rather
than hydrogen. If this is all bunkum, then it wasn't Asimov who wrote it!
- Mod.JW
